                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 King, Clifford J./1: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-06-06T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 6, 1930—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 6—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. The following telegram has been sent to the Legation: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“June 6, noon. Reverend Clifford J. King, an American missionary of the
                            Society of the Divine Word, legal residence, Techny, Illinois, currently
                            registered this Consulate, was captured by bandits in southern Honan
                            between Loshan and Chengyang near Tungchung on June 1. Details of the
                            capture not yet known. I have requested General Ho Ying-chin to take
                            every possible means to obtain the release of Reverend King. Repeated to
                            Department.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
